wE4pq-QtEePHMv-QWgpVM6nlvpG4caATvAslwICIjNVOx7bK941Mh9KFjE_d_So1V5YR1W2qOgqq2zwgXShzpZm3yOakLwaGbQR6lrHGHup6LSw8ohasx_Wt9kx4861rzWNK5FxVQbQza4___j5KprJjBe2QiVAUn\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering functionality issues**\\n\\nI see that the root URI is covered but not fully functional. I'm thinking about testing `RestTemplateBuilder.basicAuthentication` with an explicit charset. I’m curious if that would help uncover any issues or enhance functionality. It seems like a straightforward approach, but I want to ensure I’m not overlooking anything. Maybe I'll take a closer look at the implementation to see what changes could be beneficial. Let's explore this a bit more!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating plugin metadata**\\n\\nI'm noticing that the repo has a TCK plugin that uses metadata, but I think we shouldn't edit that metadata directly. Instead, it seems like we should consider using a public top-level instead. However, if we modify the test file, I realize we can't add a second top-level public class in the same file since Java only allows one public top-level class and the rest must be package-private. Using the existing `RestTemplate.class` could simplify our work since it covers the necessary features.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring RestTemplate configuration**\\n\\nI’ve got this idea about creating a public static nested class, `InstrumentedRestTemplate`, extending `RestTemplate` with a no-arg constructor. It seems there’s some question around whether having a `$` in the bytecode conflicts with naming files or classes for tests. It looks like I can test with an actual HTTP setup using a local server. I’m thinking of asserting that the same instance is returned with the expected configurations and maybe only using one header.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering RestTemplateBuilder features**\\n\\nI’m looking at the RestTemplateBuilder, which can configure a caller-provided RestTemplate while maintaining subclass type and state. That's a new feature! But there’s a restriction against retesting existing classes or logic flows since the RestTemplateBuilder is heavily tested. I’m allowed to add a method to the same class. Hmm, maybe I should explore testing something like `RestClientSsl` or `RestClientAutoConfiguration`, but I wonder about SSL requirements. I'll need to check context and dependencies with Spring Boot.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_3eVLqOWCRZLd7MOZ15waZ3M4|fc_00769cf06068227c016a0c39b83f3881a2adfe01e18b23a8fd", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "cd tests/src/org.springframework.boot/spring-boot-restclient/4.0.2 && ./gradlew dependencies --configuration testRuntimeClasspath | grep -E 'spring-(context|beans|boot-test|web|webmvc|core|aop)' | head -50", "timeout": 20}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 449, "output": 1547, "cacheRead": 14848, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 16844, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1779186077932, "responseId": "resp_00769cf06068227c016a0c399e402c81a299a2a11ed63ca95e"}}
